---
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";

const seo = {
  title: "PixiEditor Extensions | Anna Kocaj",
  description: "Fixing extension discoverability and trust for PixiEditor grew paid extension sales ~7.8x in 25 days.",
  image: "/extension_thumbnail.png",
};
---

<Layout seo={seo}>
  <!-- HERO -->
  <section class="mt-10 max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6">
    <a
      href="/projects"
      class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 opacity-50 hover:opacity-100 transition-opacity text-sm mb-8"
    >
      ← Back to projects
    </a>

    <!-- TODO: confirm exact ship date for the improvements (used May 2026 based on the 25-day window from Apr 18) -->
    <p class="text-sm opacity-50 uppercase tracking-widest mb-3 font-medium">
      Case Study · 2026
    </p>
    <h1 class="font-bold text-3xl mb-4 leading-snug">
      Fixing Extension Discoverability at PixiEditor
    </h1>
    <p class="text-lg opacity-70 mb-8 max-w-xl leading-relaxed">
      Paid extension sales grew ~7.8x in 25 days after solving a
      discoverability problem.
    </p>

    <!-- Overview grid -->
    <div
      class="grid grid-cols-2 sm:grid-cols-4 gap-4 py-6 border-t border-b border-white/10 mb-10"
    >
      <div>
        <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest opacity-40 mb-1">
          My Role
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm font-medium">
          Product Designer
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest opacity-40 mb-1">
          Timeline
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm font-medium">25 days</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest opacity-40 mb-1">Tools</p>
        <p class="text-sm font-medium">Figma, Miro</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Hero image -->
    <div class="rounded-xl overflow-hidden m-6 bg-gray-800">
      <!-- TODO: replace with a real screenshot of the redesigned extension window -->
      <Image
        src="/extension_thumbnail.png"
        alt="PixiEditor's redesigned extension browser"
        width={1200}
        height={675}
        class="w-full object-cover"
      />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHALLENGE -->
  <section class="max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6 mb-16">
    <h2 class="font-semibold text-xl mb-4">The Challenge</h2>
    <p class="opacity-70 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      PixiEditor is a free, open-source 2D graphics editor that depends on
      its community for funding. A Founders Bundle had brought in about 500
      buyers over the past year, so to grow that further we started building
      paid extensions aimed at our core users: game developers and pixel
      artists.
    </p>
    <p class="opacity-70 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      We shipped version 2.1 with a new extension browser: seven
      extensions, priced 25–124 PLN, accessible from <em
        >View &gt; Open Extensions Window</em
      >. We hadn't done any marketing yet, planning to
      market it properly once the feature had settled.
    </p>
    <p class="opacity-70 leading-relaxed">
      In the first 25 days after launch (Apr 18 – May 13), we sold <strong
        >13 extensions</strong
      >. Before spending any marketing effort, we needed to know:
      was this a marketing problem, or was something wrong with the
      product itself?
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- PROCESS -->
  <section class="max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6 mb-16">
    <h2 class="font-semibold text-xl mb-8">Process</h2>

    <div class="space-y-12">
      <!-- Step 1 -->
      <div>
        <p
          class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest opacity-40 mb-2 font-medium"
        >
          01 — Research
        </p>
        <h3 class="font-medium text-base mb-3">
          Listening before marketing
        </h3>
        <p class="opacity-70 leading-relaxed text-sm mb-4">
          Instead of promoting the extensions as-is, I gathered feedback
          from our community and grouped what came back into three distinct problems:
        </p>
        <ul class="opacity-70 leading-relaxed text-sm list-disc pl-5 space-y-2">
          <li>
            <strong>Discoverability</strong> the extension browser was
            tucked inside a submenu (<em>View &gt; Extensions</em>) and a
            small startup-window icon. Most software with a plugin
            ecosystem puts this front and center in the topbar; ours was
            effectively hidden.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Trust & clarity</strong> people couldn't tell if the
            extensions were official or community-made, and the word
            "workspace" led some users to assume it was just a custom
            view, not additional paid functionality. Combined with
            PixiEditor being free and relatively young, that ambiguity made
            people hesitant to pay for something they didn't fully
            understand.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Product readiness</strong> a smaller group of users
            were waiting on core features still on our roadmap, and didn't
            feel ready to spend money until those shipped. This was a real
            signal, but a separate problem from discoverability and trust.
            One we chose not to try to solve with this redesign.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- Step 2 -->
      <div>
        <p
          class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest opacity-40 mb-2 font-medium"
        >
          02 — Prioritize
        </p>
        <h3 class="font-medium text-base mb-3">
          Fix the entry point before spending on marketing
        </h3>
        <p class="opacity-70 leading-relaxed text-sm">
          Marketing a feature that people can't find or don't trust would
          have wasted the effort and risked making the trust problem
          worse by sending more traffic to a confusing experience. So we
          committed to fixing discoverability and clarity first, and
          holding off on any marketing push until that was live. That
          meant three concrete changes: replace the unclear icon with a
          puzzle piece (the convention users already recognize from other
          software), redesign the extension window to read as trustworthy
          and clearly explained, and surface extensions during onboarding
          instead of leaving them to be found by chance.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Step 3 -->
      <div>
        <p
          class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest opacity-40 mb-2 font-medium"
        >
          03 — Design & Ship
        </p>
        <h3 class="font-medium text-base mb-3">Three small fixes, shipped together</h3>
        <p class="opacity-70 leading-relaxed text-sm mb-4">
          I redesigned the icon as a puzzle piece so it reads instantly as
          "extensions"
        </p>
        <div class="rounded-xl overflow-hidden m-6 bg-gray-800">
          <Image
            src="/extension_icon.png"
            alt="PixiEditor extensions icon, before and after"
            width={1200}
            height={675}
            class="w-full object-cover"
          />
        </div>
        <p class="opacity-70 leading-relaxed text-sm mb-4">
          I reworked the extension window's layout and copy to make the value of each
          extension clear and the design more polished.
        </p>
        <div class="rounded-xl overflow-hidden m-6 bg-gray-800">
          <Image
            src="/extension_redesign.png"
            alt="PixiEditor's redesigned extension browser window"
            width={1200}
            height={675}
            class="w-full object-cover"
          />
        </div>
        <p class="opacity-70 leading-relaxed text-sm mb-4">
          I also added a few extensions to our onboarding flow so every new user encounters it early.
        </p>
        <div class="rounded-xl overflow-hidden m-6 bg-gray-800">
          <Image
            src="/extension_onboarding.png"
            alt="Extensions introduced during PixiEditor onboarding"
            width={1200}
            height={675}
            class="w-full object-cover"
          />
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- OUTCOMES -->
    <section class="max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6 mb-16">
      <h2 class="font-semibold text-xl mb-6">Outcomes</h2>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-3 gap-4 mb-8">
        <div class="p-5 rounded-xl border border-white/10 bg-white/5">
          <p class="text-3xl font-bold mb-1">13 sales</p>
          <p class="text-sm opacity-60">in the 25 days before the redesign</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-5 rounded-xl border border-white/10 bg-white/5">
          <p class="text-3xl font-bold mb-1">102 sales</p>
          <p class="text-sm opacity-60">in the 25 days after it shipped</p>
        </div>
      <div class="p-5 rounded-xl border border-white/10 bg-white/5">
        <p class="text-3xl font-bold mb-1">~7.8x</p>
        <p class="text-sm opacity-60">
          more extension sales thanks to the redesign
        </p>
      </div>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl overflow-hidden m-6 bg-gray-800 p-6">
        <p class="text-sm opacity-80 italic">
          "I like the new placement for the extensions. It's easier to see,
          especially because of the colour."
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs opacity-40 mt-2">
          — user feedback after the redesign shipped
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </section>

  <!-- NAVIGATION -->
  <section
    class="max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6 mb-16 flex justify-center items-center border-t border-white/10 pt-8"
  >
    <a
      href="/projects"
      class="opacity-50 hover:opacity-100 transition-opacity text-sm"
    >
      ← All projects
    </a>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  strong {
    color: white;
    font-weight: 600;
  }
  em {
    color: inherit;
  }
</style>